<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-03-24T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-03-24T08:00:00-05:00" n="1003" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1003">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">823.00 Revolutions/202: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Dearing</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-03-24T08:00:00-05:00">March 24, 1931—8
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received 11:40 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>145. My 144, March 23 [<hi rend="italic">24</hi>], 1 a.m.<note n="17" xml:id="d1003fn17">Not printed.</note> Government has dominated
                            situation. City quiet, no injury American or foreign life or property
                            yet reported. Further report in few hours.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Dearing</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>